WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.880
Hi everyone, my name is Daniel, I'm a software engineer at Posit, and today I'm going to

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:16.520
talk about what is new in the Torch ecosystem.

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:20.080
But first, what exactly is Torch?

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:27.400
So Torch is a port of PyTorch for R, and it's essentially a scientific computing library

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:38.360
providing a consistent API for computing on arrays and matrices, but it has strong support

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:43.880
for hardware acceleration, so you can run these computations on your GPU to make them

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:45.599
much faster.

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:56.080
And it also has support for a built-in automatic differentiation system in the package, so

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:01.720
it can be used for statistical and deep learning modeling.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:08.680
It is also a deep learning framework, so it implements most of the building blocks of

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:14.300
modern deep learning models, such as layers and optimizers.

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:21.760
But Torch is a big project, and just like a big city, it's hard to find your way around

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:29.320
it when you are getting started, and we hope this is much better now because we recently

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:35.199
announced the Deep Learning and Scientific Computing with R Torch book.

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:40.800
This book was written by Sigrid K. Dana, my colleague at Posit, and it is available for

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:47.559
free online, or you can buy it from CRCpress, and it covers the basics of deep learning

00:01:47.639 --> 00:01:54.680
as well as really implementing the models in Torch and R.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:02:02.680
But still, navigating in large cities is hard, and it's much easier if you have the metro,

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:05.320
and that's what Luce is for Torch.

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:11.479
So Luce abstracts away much of the boilerplate code that you need to write when training

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:20.520
deep learning models with Torch, and its API is inspired by Fast.ai and Keras, which are

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:29.880
successful libraries in Python, and so it's still very flexible and extensible with callbacks,

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:31.160
metrics, and et cetera.

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:37.639
So with Luce, you write your model exactly the same way you would write when using raw

00:02:37.639 --> 00:02:45.080
Torch, but instead of manually handling a lot of details, such as moving the model to

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:53.800
the correct device or manually iterating over your data, you let Luce do everything for

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:54.360
you.

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:59.160
So your code is cleaner, and it's also much less error prone.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:06.600
But sometimes you don't want to learn all the details and everything, and you can pick

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.839
a taxi, and that's what TabNet and Brule help in Torch.

00:03:12.199 --> 00:03:20.759
They are actually just tidy models extensions powered by Torch that you can call with single

00:03:20.759 --> 00:03:29.479
liners like this to train neural network models on tabular data, and they can also be used

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:36.600
in your usual tidy models workflows and vet deployments and et cetera.

00:03:38.119 --> 00:03:43.080
And finally, it's nice to talk with the local community.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.720
So we recently announced hugging face integrations.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.199
So we have the Torch package and the HF hub.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:04:00.440
With HF hub, you can download large models hosted in the hugging face hub.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:09.000
For example, if you were in Jeremy Howard's talk where he downloaded a llama model into

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:16.760
Python, you can do this in R using HF hub and then load the model weights into R. And

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:27.079
Torch can be used to use the exact same preprocessing pipelines as they use when training

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:27.559
the model.

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:30.600
So you get the exact same result.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:42.279
So in theory, you can run these models directly in R without even having a Python

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:44.679
installation.

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:46.839
And thank you very much.

00:04:47.799 --> 00:04:53.640
Next week, we'll be teaching Torch in the workshops for Ukraine project.

00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:58.519
And it's a nice opportunity if you want to learn more about Torch and get started.

00:04:58.519 --> 00:04:58.839
Thank you.

